# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bandy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:bandy/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] While it probably should be considered a factoid, the tournament has still been referred to as if it was a historical fact in many books and magazines about bandy and even led to a centenary celebration tournament being arranged by the Federation of International Bandy in 2014.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] The 1913 European Championship were supposedly played by national teams representing Austria, England, Belgium, Germany, Italy, Netherlands, France, and Switzerland.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] It is usually claimed to have been arranged by the International Ice Hockey Federation established in 1908 and that the teams were 7-men-teams.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] Since Sweden and Russia followed the rules of 11-men teams, they are supposed to have rejected the invitation and competed in the 1913 Nordic Games in Stockholm, where a bandy competition actually took place.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] The 1913 Nordic Games were arranged at the same time as the European Championship competition should have taken place.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] The German team consisted mostly of the members of Leipziger SC, which was supposed to play in Stockholm as well, but because many of its players were selected for the German national team, they decided to travel to Switzerland.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] On 6 January 2014, the Federation of International Bandy arranged a four nation tournament in Davos to celebrate the anniversary of the alleged 1913 European Championship.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] Czech Republic, Germany, Hungary and Netherlands played at the same venue as was thought to have been used for the competition 101 years ago.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] The Dutch won this unofficial European Championship.
[src:bandy/1913-european-bandy-championships] In 2016, a somewhat smaller tournament dubbed the Davos Cup was held with national teams from three European countries and was won by Estonia.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The **1913 Nordic Games** was the fifth Nordic Games and was held in Stockholm in February 1913.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] It was formally international sports competitions in many disciplines, but because of the communications of the time it was still mostly domestic sportspeople participating.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] Among the sports were winter sports like bandy, speed skating and skiing but also motorsports and equestrian sports.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The bandy tournament was a club tournament.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] Beside the Swedish teams, IFK Helsingfors from Finland also participated.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] Leipziger HC from Germany was scheduled to appear but the Germans eventually favoured to take part in the 1913 European Bandy Championships, which were held in Switzerland at the same time.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The Stockholm team AIK beat IFK Uppsala in the final game by 3-1.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The winter of 1913 had left Stockholm little snow, so this year the cross-country skiing was arranged in Östersund.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] Beside Swedish skiers, there were competitors from Finland, Norway and Russia.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The events were 30, 60 and 90 kilometers for men, and for women 10 kilometer.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] 90 km was the most prestigious event and this was won by Swede Haldo Hansson.
[src:bandy/1913-nordic-games] The games were depicted in the film *Nordiska spelen 1913* by cinematographer Adrian Bjurman, a film shown in several cinemas in Sweden in the same year.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Discussions about Oslo hosting the Winter Olympic Games began as early as 1935; the city was keen to host the 1948 Winter Olympics, but that was made impossible by World War II.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Instead, Oslo won the right to host the 1952 Games in a contest that included Cortina d'Ampezzo in Italy and Lake Placid in the United States.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] All of the Olympic venues were in Oslo's metropolitan area, except for the alpine skiing events, which were held at Norefjell, 113 km (70 mi) from the capital.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A new hotel was built for the press and dignitaries, along with three dormitories to house athletes and coaches, creating the first modern athlete's village.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Oslo bore the financial burden of hosting the Games in return for the revenue they generated.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The 1952 Winter Olympics was the first of the two consecutive Olympics to be held in Northern Europe, preceding the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki, Finland.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The 1952 Winter Games attracted 694 athletes representing 30 countries, who participated in four sports and 22 events.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Japan and Germany made their returns to Winter Olympic competition after being forced to miss the 1948 Games in the aftermath of World War II.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Germany was represented solely by West German athletes after East Germany declined to compete as a unified team.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Portugal and New Zealand made their Winter Olympic debuts, and women were allowed to compete in cross-country skiing for the first time.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norwegian truck driver Hjalmar Andersen won three out of four speed skating events to become the most decorated athlete of the 1952 Winter Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Germany resumed its former prominence in bobsleigh, with wins in the four- and two-man events.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Dick Button of the United States performed the first triple jump in international competition to claim his second consecutive men's figure skating Olympic title.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The popular Nordic sport bandy featured as a demonstration sport, but only three Nordic countries competed in the tournament.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norway dominated the overall medal count with 16 medals, including seven golds.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Games closed with the presentation of a flag that would be passed to the host city of the next Winter Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The flag, which became known as the "Oslo flag", has been displayed in the host city during subsequent Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Oslo had unsuccessfully bid to host the 1936 Winter Olympics, losing to Germany, which had hosted the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] At that time, the nation that hosted the Summer Olympics also hosted the Winter Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] After the 1936 Games, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) decided to award the Winter and Summer Games to different countries, but the Games were suspended during World War II.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] London hosted the first post-war Games, the 1948 Summer Olympics, and recommended Oslo as the host city for the 1948 Winter Games, but the city council declined.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Instead, the 1948 Winter Olympics were held in St.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norwegians were undecided about hosting a Winter Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Culturally, they were opposed to competitive winter sports, particularly skiing events, despite the success of Norwegian athletes at previous Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] But the organizers believed the 1952 Games could be an opportunity to promote national unity and to show the world that Norway had recovered from the war.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Vying with Oslo for the right to host the Games were Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy, and Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The IOC voted to award the 1952 Winter Games to Oslo on 21 June 1947 at the 40th IOC Session in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Later, Cortina d'Ampezzo was awarded the 1956 Games, and Lake Placid—which had hosted the 1932 Winter Olympics—was chosen to host the 1980 Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norway became the first Scandinavian country to host a Winter Olympics, and the 1952 Winter Games were the first to be held in a nation's capital.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A special committee was assigned to organize the 1952 Games, which consisted of four Norwegian sports officials and four representatives from the municipality of Oslo, including mayor Brynjulf Bull.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The committee was in place by December 1947.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The city of Oslo funded the Games entirely, in exchange for keeping all the revenue generated.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] To accommodate the influx of athletes and coaches, quarters for competitors and support staff were designed and constructed, with three new facilities (forerunners of the athlete's villages of later Games) built.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The city of Oslo paid to have a new hotel constructed, the Viking, used for IOC delegates, out-of-town dignitaries, and as the communication hub of the Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] For the first time in a Winter Games, an indoor ice hockey arena was constructed, which hosted the eight-team tournament.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Oslo's existing central arena, Bislett Stadium, was used for the opening and closing ceremonies, and for speed skating events.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Improvements to the arena included better sound and lighting systems, remodeled club house and press rooms, and the addition of a medical center.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] In the aftermath of the German occupation of Norway during World War II, anti-German sentiment began to affect preparations for the 1952 Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Discussions were held to consider whether Germany should be allowed to participate in the Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] When in 1950, the West German Olympic Committee requested recognition by the IOC, it raised the question of whether their participation would cause political boycotts in the upcoming Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Once the IOC recognized the West German Olympic Committee, West Germany was then formally invited to compete at the 1952 Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] East Germany was invited to participate with West Germany, as a unified team, but they declined.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] At first Norway was reluctant to welcome German athletes and others considered Nazi sympathizers.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] For example, Norwegian speed skater Finn Hodt was not allowed to compete in the Norwegian speed skating team because he collaborated with the Nazis during the war.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Eventually, despite the concern, Norway agreed to allow German and Japanese athletes to compete.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union sent no athletes to Oslo, despite being recognized by the IOC, sending observers instead.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 22 events contested in four sports (eight disciplines).
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The opening ceremonies were held in Bislett Stadium on 15 February.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] King George VI of Great Britain had died on 6 February 1952 with his daughter Elizabeth II taking the throne as Queen, eight days before the start of the Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] As a result, all national flags were flown at half-mast, and Princess Ragnhild opened the Games in place of her grandfather, King Haakon VII, who was in London attending the state funeral.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] This was the first time an Olympic Games had been declared open by a female official.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The parade of nations was held according to tradition, with Greece first and the rest of the nations proceeding by alphabetical order in the Norwegian language, with the host nation last.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The British, Australian, Canadian and New Zealand teams all wore black arm bands at the opening ceremonies in memory of their monarch.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Following the parade of nations, the Olympic flame was lit.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] On 13 February, at the start of the inaugural Winter Olympics torch relay, the torch was lit in the hearth of the Morgedal House, birthplace of skiing pioneer Sondre Norheim.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The torch relay lasted two days and was conducted entirely on skis.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] At the opening ceremonies the final torch bearer, Eigil Nansen, received the Olympic torch and skied to a flight of stairs where he removed his skis, ascended, and ignited the flame.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh and alpine skiing events were held the day before the opening ceremonies.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Competitors in these events were unable to attend the festivities in Oslo; consequently simple opening ceremonies were held at Frognerseteren, site of the bobsleigh events, and Norefjell, site of the alpine skiing events.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] After a 16-year hiatus from the Olympics, Germany made a triumphant return to the bobsleigh competition, winning the two- and four-man events.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The results for both bobsleigh events were the same, with the United States and Switzerland taking silver and bronze respectively.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Fritz Feierabend from Switzerland competed in both the two- and four-man competitions.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] His two bronze medals were the fourth and fifth in an Olympic career that spanned 16 years and three Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] There were no weight restrictions on the bobsleigh athletes, and the average weight for each member of the winning German four-man team was 117 kg (258 lb), which was more than the Olympic heavyweight boxing champion in 1952.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Seeing the undue advantage overweight athletes brought to their teams, the International Federation for Bobsleigh and Toboganning instituted a weight limit for future Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] All of the speed skating events were held at Bislett Stadium.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Americans Ken Henry and Don McDermott placed first and second in the 500-meter race, but Norwegian truck driver Hjalmar Andersen electrified the partisan crowd by winning the 1,500, 5,000 and 10,000-meter events; his margins of victory were the largest in Olympic history.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Dutchman Wim van der Voort placed second in the 1,500 meters and his countryman Kees Broekman placed second to Andersen in the 5,000 and 10,000-meter races, becoming the first Olympic speed skating medalists from the Netherlands.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Absent from the competition was former world champion Kornél Pajor.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Hungarian-born speed skater had won both long-distance races at the World Championships held in Oslo in 1949 and then defected to Sweden, but was unable to obtain Swedish citizenship in time to compete in 1952.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] There were three alpine skiing events on the Olympic program: the slalom, giant slalom and downhill.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Both men and women competed in all three events, held at Norefjell and Rødkleiva.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The giant slalom made its Olympic debut at the 1952 Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Austrian skiers dominated the competition, winning seven out of a possible 18 medals, including Othmar Schneider who won gold and silver in the men's slalom and downhill.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norwegian Stein Eriksen won gold in the men's giant slalom and silver in the slalom.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Greek slalom skier Antoin Miliordos fell 18 times on his run and crossed the finish line backwards.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] American skier Andrea Mead Lawrence was the only double gold medalist, winning the giant slalom and the slalom.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] She was the first skier from the United States to win two alpine skiing gold medals.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] All the cross-country events were held next to the ski jump hill at Holmenkollbakken.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] As had been the case in 1948 there were three men's events: 18 kilometers, 50 kilometers, and a relay.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Added to the Olympic program for the first time was a ten-kilometer race for women.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] All the cross-country medals were won by Nordic countries, and Finnish skiers won eight of the twelve possible.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Lydia Wideman of Finland became the first female Olympic champion in cross-country skiing; her teammates Mirja Hietamies and Siiri Rantanen won silver and bronze respectively.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Veikko Hakulinen won the 50-kilometer men's race to begin an Olympic career that would culminate in seven medals, three of them gold.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Hallgeir Brenden won the 18-kilometer race and helped Norway take the silver in the 4 × 10-kilometer relay.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Brenden went on to win another gold in the men's 15-kilometer race in 1956, and a silver in the relay in 1960.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The nordic combined event was held at the cross-country and ski jump venues.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] For the first time, the ski jump part took place first with competitors taking three jumps from the Holmenkollbakken.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The 18-km cross country skiing event took place the next day.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Results were tallied by the best two marks were scored, along with the results of the cross-country race, to determine a winner.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norwegians Simon Slåttvik and Sverre Stenersen won the gold and bronze respectively.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Stenersen went on to win the gold at the 1956 Games in the same event.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Heikki Hasu from Finland won the silver, preventing a Norwegian sweep of the medals.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Crowds in excess of 100,000 greeted the ski jumpers as they competed at Holmenkollbakken.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] In 1952 there was only one event, the men's normal hill, which was held on 24 February.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The King, Prince Harald, and Princess Ragnhild were in attendance.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Norwegian athletes did not disappoint the crowd, as Arnfinn Bergmann and Torbjørn Falkanger placed first and second; Swedish jumper Karl Holmström took the bronze.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Norwegian athletes won the ski jumping gold medal in every Winter Olympics from 1924 to 1952.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] There were three events in the Olympic figure skating competition: men's singles, women's singles and mixed pairs.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The events were held at Bislett Stadium on a rink constructed inside the speed skating track.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Dick Button of the United States won the men's singles event.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Helmut Seibt of Austria took silver and James Grogan of the United States won bronze.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Button became the first figure-skater to land a triple jump in competition when he performed the triple loop in the men's free skate.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] British skater Jeannette Altwegg won the gold medal in the women's singles, the silver was won by American Tenley Albright, who went on to win gold at the 1956 Winter Games in Cortina d'Ampezzo, and Jacqueline du Bief of France won the bronze.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The German husband and wife pair of Ria and Paul Falk won the mixed pairs competition.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] They defeated Americans Karol and Peter Kennedy, who placed second, and Hungarian siblings Marianna and László Nagy, who won the bronze medal.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A majority of the ice hockey matches took place at Jordal Amfi, a new hockey stadium built for the Olympics.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Nine teams played in the tournament and Canada again won the gold medal.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Canada had won all but one Olympic hockey tournament thus far, but in 1956 the Soviet team began to compete and ended Canadian dominance.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Canada was represented by the Edmonton Mercurys, an amateur hockey team sponsored by the owner of a Mercury automobile dealership.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Canada played the United States to a three all tie on the final day to clinch the gold, and the Americans won silver.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The official report of the USOC for the 1952 Olympics covers the game in great detail.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] According to the report, by the end of the game against Canada, the Americans were mentally and physically exhausted and after scoring the third goal and tying the game they decided to focus on defense in order not to lose silver.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Canadians at the time were considered unbeatable.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Sweden and Czechoslovakia ended up tied for third (Czechoslovakia defeated the Swedes in the head-to-head game, but according to the rules at the time they had to play a tiebreaker game because they were tied in points).
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Sweden won that game and avenged the loss in the round-robin.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Czechs believed they had already won the bronze when they defeated the Swedes in the round-robin, calling the decision to play a tie-breaking game a "plot of the capitalist countries".
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Canadian team was criticized for its rough play; although body checking was legal, it was not often used by European teams, and opponents and spectators alike took a dim view of that style of play.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The IOC lobbied the organizing committee to host either military patrol or curling as a demonstration sport.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The committee instead selected bandy, which had never been included in the Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Popular in Nordic countries, bandy is played by teams of eleven on an outdoor soccer field-sized ice rink, using a small ball and sticks about 1.2 m (3.9 ft) long.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] As it was a demonstration sport, the players were ineligible for medals.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Three nations participated: Finland, Norway and Sweden.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Each of the three teams won one game and lost one game; with Sweden winning the competition based on number of goals scored, followed by Norway in second place, and Finland in third place.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Two of the games were played at Dæhlenenga Stadium and one at Bislett Stadium.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] At the 1952 Winter Games, the closing ceremonies were a distinct program listing, unlike previous Winter Games when the closing ceremonies were held directly after the final event.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The closing ceremonies were held in Bislett Stadium, on Monday evening, 25 February.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The flag bearers entered the stadium in the same order they followed for the opening ceremonies.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] That evening four medal ceremonies were also held for the women's cross-country race, the men's cross-country relay, the ski jumping competition, and the ice hockey tournament.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Since 1920, the "Antwerp flag" has been passed from host city to host city during closing ceremonies for the Summer Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The city of Oslo gave an Olympic flag to establish the same tradition for the Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Brynjulf Bull, Oslo's mayor, passed the flag to the president of the IOC, Sigfrid Edström, who declared the flag was to pass from host city to host city for future Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The flag, which came to be known as the "Oslo Flag", has since been preserved in a display case, with the name of every Winter Olympics host city engraved on brass plaques, and is brought to each Winter Games to be displayed.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A replica is used during the closing ceremonies.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] After the flag ceremony the Olympic flame was extinguished, a special speed skating race was held, and the figure skating competitors gave an exhibition, followed by 40 children dressed in national costumes performing an ice dance.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] For a finale, to the close the Games, the lights were extinguished and a 20-minute fireworks display lit up the night sky.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] With a seating capacity of 29,000, Bislett Stadium became the centrepiece of the Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] It was the venue for the speed skating events and the figure skating competition.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Bislett was large enough for a 400 m (1,300 ft) speed skating track, and a figure skating ice-rink of 30 by 60 m (98 by 197 ft); a snow bank separated the track and the rink.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Because Bislett was an outdoor arena, the organizing committee chose Tryvann Stadion and Hamar Stadion as secondary alternative skating venues to be used the case of bad weather.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] In 1994 Hamar became the venue for the speed skating events at the 1994 Winter Olympics in Lillehammer.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The Oslo Winter Games were the first to feature an Olympic ice hockey tournament held on artificial ice.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A new stadium was built for the hockey tournament in a residential area of eastern Oslo, called Jordal Amfi, which accommodated 10,000 spectators in stands rising steeply from the rink.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] 23 of the 36 hockey matches were played at Jordal Amfi, with the remaining matches played at Kadettangen, Dælenenga idrettspark, Lillestrøm Stadion and Marienlyst Stadion.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The cross-country races and ski-jump competition were held at Holmenkollbakken, located roughly 8 km (5 mi) from the center of Oslo.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The expected number of spectators caused concerns about traffic, so a new road was constructed and the existing thoroughfare widened.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Holmenkollbakken was built in 1892 and improvements were needed to meet international standards.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The original wood ski-jump was replaced with a concrete tower and jump that was 87 m (285 ft) long.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] New stands were built to seat 13,000 people, and an area was added at the base of the hill to accommodate 130,000 spectators.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The hills and terrain in the surrounding area met the competitive demands for an elite cross-country ski event.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A notice board was posted at the start and finish lines to help spectators monitor the progress of the competitors.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The cross-country and Nordic combined races began and ended at the base of the ski jump hill.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The stands for the ski jump competition had to be removed during the cross-country races; spectators had only a small area from which to watch the races but were allowed on the course to cheer on the competitors.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The alpine skiing events were split between Norefjell and Rødkleiva.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The slalom courses were at Rødkleiva, located on the same mountain as Holmenkollen and Frognerseteren.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The course had an elevation difference, from start to finish, of 200 m (660 ft) and was 480 m (1,570 ft) in length.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A rope tow had to be built to bring the skiers from the bottom to the top of the hill.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The downhill race and the giant slalom—which made its Olympic debut in 1952—were held at Norefjell, which was 113 km (70 mi) from Oslo and the only venue located away from the capital city.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Work had to be done to make the area suitable for Olympic competition.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A bridge across Lake Krøderen was built to help alleviate transportation congestion.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A new hotel, two ski lifts, and a new road were also constructed.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] There was no permanent bobsleigh run in Norway.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Instead the organizers built a temporary course out of snow and ice.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] This is often wrongly assumed to have been built at Korketrekkeren.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] From Frognerseteren a separate 1,508 m (4,948 ft) long, 13-turn course was designed and built.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh run was first constructed and tested in 1951, then rebuilt for the Games in 1952.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] A car was used to return the bobsleighs to the start of the track.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Thirty nations sent competitors, which was the highest number of participants at a Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] New Zealand and Portugal took part in the Winter Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] Australia, Germany, and Japan returned after a 16-year absence.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] South Korea, Liechtenstein, and Turkey competed in 1948 but did not participate in the 1952 Games.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] The official opening ceremonies were held on 15 February, although two smaller ceremonies were held on 14 February to conform with competition schedules.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] From 15 February until 25 February, the day of the closing ceremonies, at least one event final was held each day.
[src:bandy/1952-winter-olympics] These are the nations that topped the medal count at the 1952 Winter Games.
[src:bandy/1965-bandy-world-championship] The **1965 Bandy World Championship** was the fourth Bandy World Championship and was contested by four men's bandy playing nations.
[src:bandy/1965-bandy-world-championship] The championship was played in five cities of the Soviet Union (Arkhangelsk, Ivanovo, Kursk, Moscow and Sverdlovsk) on February 21–27, 1965.
[src:bandy/1991-bandy-world-championship] The **1991 Bandy World Championship** was contested by eight men's bandy playing nations in Finland from 17 to 24 March 1991.
[src:bandy/1991-bandy-world-championship] Canada, Hungary and the Netherlands made their championship debuts.
[src:bandy/1991-bandy-world-championship] The Soviet Union became champions in what would be its last tournament; less than a year later, the Soviet Union was dissolved and was briefly replaced in international bandy by the Commonwealth of Independent States, and then permanently by Russia.
[src:bandy/1991-bandy-world-championship] The final game was played at Oulunkylä Ice Rink in Helsinki.
[src:bandy/1999-bandy-world-championship] The **1999 Bandy World Championship** was a competition between bandy playing nations for men.
[src:bandy/1999-bandy-world-championship] The championship was played in Arkhangelsk, Russia, between 30 January and 7 February 1999, with six teams contesting.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The playing surface, called a bandy field or bandy rink, is a sheet of ice which measures 90–110 metres (300–360 ft) by 45–65 metres (148–213 ft), about the size of a football pitch.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The field is considerably larger than the ice rinks commonly used for ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport has a common background with association football, ice hockey, shinty, and field hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy's origins are debatable, but its first rules were organized and published in England in 1882.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Internationally, bandy's strongest nations in both men's and women's competitions have long been Sweden and Russia; both countries have established professional men's bandy leagues.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Russia, it is estimated that more than one million people play bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport also has organized league play and fans in other countries, including Finland, Norway, and Kazakhstan.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The premier international bandy competition for men is the Bandy World Championship and for women it is the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Organized bandy started in the late 19th century; however, until 1955, there was no established international governing body for the sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The international governing body for bandy today is the Federation of International Bandy (FIB) which formed in February 1955.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In 2001, bandy was recognized as a sport by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Both traditional eleven-a-side bandy and rink bandy (which is played on a smaller rink) are recognized by the IOC.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Based on the number of participating athletes, the FIB has claimed bandy is the world's second-most participated winter sport after ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The earliest origin of the sport is debated.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The mid-eighteenth-century *Devonshire Dialogue* collection lists Bandy as "a game, like that of Golf, in which the adverse parties endeavour to beat a ball (generally a knob or gnarl from the trunk of a tree,) opposite ways... the stick with which the game is played is crook'd at the end".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport's first published set of organized rules was codified in 1882 by Charles Goodman Tebbutt of the Bury Fen Bandy Club.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] When the international federation was founded in 1955, it came about after a compromise between Russian and English rules, in which more of the English rules prevailed.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Since association football was already popular in England, the codified bandy rules took after much of the football rules.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Like association football, games are normally two 45 minute halves and there are 11 players per side.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Players sticks are curved like large field hockey sticks and the bandy ball is roughly the size of a tennis ball with a cork core and hard plastic coating.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy balls were originally usually red but are now either orange or more commonly cerise.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy as an ice skating sport first developed in England.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It developed as a winter sport in the Fens of East Anglia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Large expanses of ice would form on the flooded meadows or shallow washes in cold winters where fen skating, which has been a tradition dating back to at least medieval times, took place.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy's early recorded modernization period can be traced back to 1813.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Members of the Bury Fen Bandy Club published rules of the game in 1882, and introduced it into other European countries.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A variety of stick and ball games involving ice skating were introduced to North America by the 1800s but failed to organize and develop popular rules codes.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, these stick and ball games became one of the eventual antecedents of the modern sport of ice hockey, whose first rules were codified in Canada in 1875.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The first international bandy match took place in 1891 between Bury Fen and the Haarlemsche Hockey & Bandy Club from the Netherlands (a club which after a couple of club fusions now is named HC Bloemendaal).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The same year, the National Bandy Association was established as a governing body for the sport in England.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] National governing federations for bandy were also founded in the 1890s in the Netherlands and Russia and in the following decade in Finland (then part of the Russian Empire), Sweden, and Norway.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The match later dubbed "the original bandy match", was actually held in 1875 at The Crystal Palace in London.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, at the time, the game was called "hockey on the ice", probably as it was considered an ice variant of field hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] An early maker of bandy sticks was the firm of Gray's, Cambridge.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] One such stick, now in the collections of the Museum of Cambridge, has a length of rope twisted round the handle to rescue any player who might fall through the ice, as the game was played on frozen lakes back then.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] An 1899 photo of two players demonstrating the game shows the sticks being held single-handed.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Historically, bandy was a popular sport in some central and western European countries until the First World War, and from 1901 to 1926 it was played in the Scandinavian Nordic Games, the first international multi-sport event focused on winter sports.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The first national bandy league in modern history was started in Sweden in 1902.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy was played at the Nordic Games in both Stockholm and Kristiania (present day Oslo) in 1901, 1903, 1905, 1909, 1913, 1917, 1922 and 1926, and between Swedish, Finnish and Russian teams at similar games in Helsinki in 1907.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy appeared as a sport in all eight editions of the Nordic Games from 1901 to 1926.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Spartakiad was an international multisport event arranged by workers' sports clubs in the 1920s and 1930s and sponsored by the Soviet Union.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In the first Winter Spartakiad, held in Oslo, Norway, in 1928, bandy was played by teams from Norway, the Soviet Union and Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy was played as a demonstration sport at the 1952 Oslo Olympics.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Finland defeated Norway 3-2 in front of 500 fans.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Norway then took on the Swedes later that day, with 3000 people watching as the underdog Norwegians defeated Sweden 2-1, which was their first recorded victory versus their larger neighbor.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In the final game, Sweden beat Finland 4-0.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport's English name comes from the verb "to bandy", from the Middle French *bander* ("to strike back and forth"), and originally referred to a seventeenth-century Irish game similar to field hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The curved stick was also called a "bandy".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The etymological connection to the similarly named Welsh hockey game of bando is not clear.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] An old name for bandy is *hockey on the ice*; in the first rule books from England at the turn of the century 1900, the sport is literally called "bandy or hockey on the ice".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Since the early 20th century, the term bandy is usually preferred to prevent confusion with ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport is known as bandy in many languages, with a few exceptions.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Russia, bandy is called "Russian hockey" (русский хоккей) or more frequently, and officially, "hockey with a ball" (хоккей с мячом) while ice hockey is called "hockey with a puck" (хоккей с шайбой) or more frequently just "hockey".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If the context makes it clear that bandy is the subject, it as well can be called just "hockey".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Belarusian, Ukrainian and Bulgarian it is also called "hockey with a ball" (хакей з мячoм, хокей з м'ячем and хокей с топка respectively).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Slovak "bandy hockey" (*bandyhokej*) is the name.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Armenian, Kazakh, Kyrgyz, Mongol and Uzbek, bandy is known as "ball hockey" (գնդակով հոկեյ, допты хоккей, топтуу хоккей, бөмбөгтэй хоккей and *koptokli xokkey* respectively).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Finnish the two sports are distinguished as "ice ball" (*jääpallo*) and "ice puck" (*jääkiekko*), as well as in Hungarian (*jéglabda; jégkorong*), although in Hungarian it is more often called "bandy" nowadays.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Estonian and Lithuanian bandy is also called "ice ball" (*jääpall*; *ledo riedulys*).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Mandarin Chinese it is "bandy ball" (班迪球).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Scottish Gaelic the name is "ice shinty" (*camanachd-deighe*).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In old times shinty or shinney were also sometimes used in English for bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Because of its similarities with association football, bandy is also nicknamed "winter football" (Swedish: *Vinterns fotboll*).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It is natural that bandy got the nickname 'winter football'.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It was common for sports clubs to have both a bandy and a football section, with athletes playing both sports but at different times of the year.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Some examples are *Nottingham Forest Football and Bandy Club* in England (today known just as Nottingham Forest F.C.) and Norwegian Strømsgodset IF and Mjøndalen IF, with both having an active bandy section.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Sweden, most football clubs that were active during the first half of the 20th century also played bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Swedish player Orvar Bergmark earned silver medals in the world championships of both sports in the 1950s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Later, as the season for each sport increased in time, it was not as easy for the players to engage in both sports, so some clubs came to concentrate on one or the other.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Many old clubs still have both sports on their program.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sten-Ove Ramberg is the last Swedish male player in both national teams (1978 in bandy, 1979–1984 in football).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] No clear distinction between bandy and ice hockey was made before the 1920s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] As bandy in a way can be seen as a precursor to ice hockey, bandy has influenced the development and history of ice hockey, mainly in European and former Soviet countries.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] While modern ice hockey was created in Canada, a variety of games which bore a closer resemblance to bandy were initially played there after British soldiers introduced the game of bandy in the late 19th century.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] At the same time as modern ice hockey rules were formalized in British North America (present-day Canada), bandy rules were decided upon in Europe.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Before Canadians introduced ice hockey into Europe in the early 20th century, "hockey" was another name for bandy, and still is in parts of Russia and Kazakhstan.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Both bandy and ice hockey were played in Europe during the 20th century, especially in Sweden, Finland, and Norway.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Ice hockey became more popular than bandy in most of Europe, mostly because it had become an Olympic sport, while bandy had not.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Athletes in Europe who had played bandy switched to ice hockey in the 1920s to compete in the Olympics.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The smaller ice fields needed for ice hockey also made its rinks easier to maintain, especially in countries with short winters.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] On the other hand, ice hockey was not played in the Soviet Union until the 1950s, when the USSR wanted to compete internationally.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The typical European style of ice hockey, with flowing, less physical play, represents a heritage of bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Since the 1950s, when the Soviet Union ended its isolation and started to take part in international sports events, there has been a reason to play world championships.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The International Bandy Federation was founded in 1955 and the first world championships were played in 1957 with the Soviet Union and then Russia (as its successor country in 1993) almost consistently in a top position in the sport of bandy alongside Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In a similar fashion, Russia, along with Sweden, has emerged as one of the two dominant women's bandy nations internationally in the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Women's bandy uses the exact same rules as men, but the women's game is played separately.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Women have been playing bandy since the sport was originally developed.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Although there were several attempts in the early part of the 19th century to organize bandy leagues for women's teams, regular leagues only started in the 1970s in Sweden and Finland and then later in the 1980s in Norway and the Soviet Union.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The highest altitude where bandy has been played is in Khorugh, the capital of the Tajik autonomous province of Gorno-Badakhshan.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Khorugh is situated 2,200 metres (7,200 feet) above sea level in the Pamir Mountains.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Starting in the 1980s and increasingly since the turn of the millennium, more and more indoor arenas for bandy have been built (often as joint arenas to be used also for football or speed skating).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The use of indoor arenas makes the effects of the weather on a game virtually insignificant, something which earlier always have been a factor to consider for the teams and the audiences.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, unlike some other sports, bandy is still the same game with the same rules indoors or outdoors and no changes are made to the rules depending on whether there's a roof overhead or not.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Many games, even in the highest leagues, are still played outdoors.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Sweden there are more indoor arenas than in all other countries combined.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy is played on ice, using a single round bandy ball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Two teams of 11 players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal using bandy sticks, thereby scoring a goal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If both teams have scored an equal number of goals, then, with some exceptions, the game is a draw.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The game is designed to be played on a rectangular sheet of ice, called a bandy field, which is the same size as a football (soccer) field.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In a typical game, players attempt to propel the ball toward their opponents' goal through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or tackling the opponent who controls the ball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, physical contact between opponents is limited.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play, or when play is stopped by the referee.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] After a stoppage, play can recommence with a free stroke, a penalty shot or a corner stroke.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If the ball has left the field along the sidelines, the referee must decide which team touched the ball last, and award a restart stroke to the opposing team, just like football's throw-in.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In terms of rules, bandy has several rules that are similar to football.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Each team has 11 players, one of whom is a goalkeeper.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Goalkeepers use gloves made specifically for their position and wear them on both hands but do not use any type of stick.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The offside rule, which in general is similar to the one used in football, is also employed.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A goal cannot be scored from a goal throw, but unlike football, a goal can be scored from a stroke-in.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] All free strokes are "direct" and allow a goal to be scored without another player touching the ball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A primary rule is that players (other than the goalkeepers) may not intentionally touch the ball with their heads, hands or arms during play.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Although players usually use their sticks to move the ball around, they may use any part of their bodies other than their heads, hands or arms and may use their skates in a limited manner.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The rules do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of player specialisations have evolved.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to discern them from the single goalkeeper.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] These positions are further differentiated by which side of the field the player spends most time in.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] For example, there are central defenders, and left and right midfielders.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] While players may spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The layout of the players on the pitch is called the team's formation, and defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager(s).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Formation in bandy is often comparable to the formation in association football.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Shouldering is allowed in checking situations and body contact therefore does occur, but body checking and fighting are illegal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Elite players have a mean skating velocity of over 16 km/h (10 mph) and the skating velocity can in some cases reach 37 km/h (23 mph).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There are eighteen rules in official play, designed to apply to all levels of bandy, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, veterans or women are permitted.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The rules are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A game is officiated by a referee, the authority and enforcer of the rules, whose decisions are final.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The referee may have one or two assistant referees.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A secretary outside of the field often takes care of the match protocol.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Bandy Playing Rules can be found on the official website of the Federation of International Bandy, and are overseen by the Rules and Referee Committee.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Each team consists of a maximum of 11 players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A team of fewer than eight players may not start a game.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, and they are only allowed to do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the rules of the game.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The positions and formations of the players in bandy are virtually the same as the common association football positions and the same terms are used for the different positions of the players.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A team usually consists of defenders, midfielders and forwards.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The defenders can play in the form of centre-backs, full-backs and sometimes wing-backs, midfielders playing in the centre, attacking or defensive, and forwards in the form of centre forward, second strikers and sometimes a winger.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sometimes one player is also taking up the role of a libero.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Any number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Substitutions can be performed without notifying the referee and can be performed while the ball is in play.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, the substitute must leave the ice before the teammate enters it.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A team can bring at the most four substitutes to the game, five if one of these is an extra goalkeeper.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Formation in bandy describes how the players in a team generally position themselves on the rink and is often comparable to the formation in association football.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The team's manager(s) define the team's formation while tactics are usually their prerogative as well.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy is a fluid and fast-moving game, and (with the exception of the goalkeeper) a player's position in a formation defines their role less rigidly than — for instance — for a rugby player, nor are there episodes in play where players must expressly line up in formation (as in gridiron football).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The bandy games are more similar to association football in this regard.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Nevertheless, a player's position in a formation generally defines whether a player has a mostly defensive or attacking role, and whether they tend to play towards one side of the pitch or centrally.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A standard adult bandy match consists of two periods of 45 minutes each, known as halves.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Each half runs continuously, meaning the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play; the referee can, however, make allowance for time lost through significant stoppages as described below.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This added time is commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury-time*, and must be reported to the match secretary and the two captains.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If it is very cold or if it is snowing, the match can be broken into thirds of 30 minutes each.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] At the extremely cold 1999 World Championship some matches were played in four periods of 15 minutes each and with extra long breaks in between.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In the World Championships the two halves can be 30 minutes each for the nations in the B division.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In league competitions, games may end in a draw, but in some knockout competitions if a game is tied at the end of regulation time it may go into extra time, which usually consists of two further 10-minute periods.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If the score is still tied after extra time, the game will be decided on penalties.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The teams shoot five penalties each and if this doesn't settle the game, the teams shoot one more penalty each until one of them misses and the other scores.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Under the rules, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] From the beginning of each playing period with a stroke-off (a set strike from the centre-spot by one team) until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If the time runs out while a team is preparing for a free-stroke or penalty, the strike should still be made but it must go into the goal by one shot to count as a goal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Similarly, a goal made via a corner stroke should be allowed, but it must be executed using only one shot in addition to the strike needed to put the ball in play.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Free-strokes can be awarded to a team if a player of the opposite team breaks any rule, for example, by hitting with the stick against the opponent's stick or skates.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Free-strokes can also be awarded upon incorrect execution of corner-strikes, free-strikes, goal-throws, and so on, or the use of incorrect equipment, such as a broken stick.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue when its continuation will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within a short period of time, typically taken to be four to five seconds.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Even if an offence is not penalised because the referee plays an advantage, the offender may still be sanctioned (see below) for any associated misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] If a defender violently attacks an opponent within the penalty area, a penalty shot is awarded.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Certain other offences, when carried out within the penalty area, for instance a defender holding or hooking an attacker, or blocking a goal situation with a lifted skate, thrown stick or glove and so on result in a penalty shot.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Also, the defenders (with the exception of the goal-keeper) are not allowed to kneel or lie on the ice.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The final offences that might mandate a penalty shot are those of hitting or blocking an opponent's stick or touching the ball with the hands, arms, stick or head.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A 10-minute penalty or a red card may be issued to the offending player as well.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A yellow card indicates a warning given to an entire team for technical fouls such as errors in the execution of goal-throws or free strokes, or the obstruction of a player without ball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Subsequent technical fouls by the same team result in a five-minute penalty indicated by a white card.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A five-minute penalty is traditionally indicated using a white card but today the card is rarely shown, rather an announcement from the match secretary or the referee is used instead.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In a similar manner, traditionally a ten-minute penalty is indicated by use of a blue card.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A ten-minute penalty can be given for protesting or behaving incorrectly, attacking an opponent violently or stopping the ball incorrectly to get an advantage.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The third time a player receives a time penalty, it will be a personal penalty, meaning he or she will miss the remainder of the match.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A substitute can enter the field after five or ten minutes, depending on the type of time penalty received.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A full game penalty can be received upon using abusive language or directly attacking an opponent and means that the player can neither play nor be substituted for the remainder of the game.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A match penalty is indicated through the use of a red card.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The offside rule effectively limits the ability to attack players to remain forward (i.e. closer to the opponent's goal-line) of the ball, the second-to-last defending player (which can include the goalkeeper), and the half-way line.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This rule is in general similar to that of soccer.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The basic equipment players are required to wear includes a pair of bandy skates, a helmet, a mouthguard and, in the case of the goalkeeper, a faceguard.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The teams must wear uniforms that make it easy to distinguish the two teams.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The goalkeeper wears distinct colours to be singled out from his or her teammates, just as in football.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The ice skates, sticks and any tape on the stick must be of another colour than the bandy ball, which is orange or cerise.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In addition to the aforementioned items, various pieces of gear are used to protect the knees, elbows, genitals and throat.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The pants and gloves may contain padding.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The core of the ball is made of cork and is surrounded by rubber or rubber-like plastic.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Balls should be manufactured in a diameter of 62.4 or 63.8 mm (2.46 or 2.51 in) (the latter is called a "Russian ball").
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Originally, bandy balls were red, then later became orange or cerise.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] According to the Bandy Playing Rules set up by the Federation of International Bandy, any of these are allowed, but all balls used in one game must be of the same colour and type.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The stick used in bandy is an essential part of the sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It should be made of an approved material such as wood or a similar material and should not contain any metal or sharp parts which can hurt the surrounding players.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sticks are crooked and are available in five angles, where 1 has the smallest bend and 5 has the most.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bend 4 is the most common size in professional bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The bandy stick should not have similar colours to the ball, such as orange or pink; it should be no longer than 127 centimetres (50 in), and no wider than 7 centimetres (2.8 in).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A bandy field is 45–65 metres (148–213 ft) by 90–110 metres (300–360 ft), a total of 4,050–7,150 square metres (43,600–77,000 sq ft), or about the same size as a football pitch and considerably larger than an ice hockey rink, which is 25–30 metres (82–98 ft) by 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Along the sidelines a 15 cm (6 in) high border (vant, sarg, wand, wall) is placed to prevent the ball from leaving the ice.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It should not be attached to the ice, to glide upon collisions, and should end 1–3 metres (3 ft 3 in – 9 ft 10 in) away from the corners.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Centered at each shortline is a 3.5 m (11 ft) wide and 2.1 m (6 ft 11 in) high goal cage and in front of the cage is a half-circular penalty area with a 17 m (56 ft) radius.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A penalty spot is located 12 metres (39 ft) in front of the goal and there are two free-stroke spots at the penalty area line, each surrounded by a 5 m (16 ft) circle.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A centre spot with a circle of radius 5 m (16 ft) denotes the center of the field.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] A centre-line is drawn through the centre spot parallel with the shortlines.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] At each of the corners, a 1 m (3 ft 3 in) radius quarter-circle is drawn, and a dotted line is painted parallel to the shortline and 5 metres (16 ft) away from it without extending into the penalty area.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The dotted line can be replaced with a 0.5-metre (1 ft 8 in) long line starting at the edge of the penalty area and extending towards the sideline, 5 metres (16 ft) from the shortline.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The goal cage used in bandy is3.5 m (11 ft) wide and 2.1 metres (6 feet 11 inches) high and is the largest one used by any organized winter team sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy players require protective equipment, some of which is designed specifically for the sport such as the bandy chinguard.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Equipment is similar to that worn in ice hockey but is typically smaller, lighter, and more flexible, and more closely resembles the equipment worn in the modern sport of ringette.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] All players are required to wear helmets.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] While some bandy players are required to wear facemasks such as young players, some outfield players only wear a helmet with a bandy chin guard.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Goaltenders are the exception and must wear a helmet and facemask at all times.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The first international games were played by club teams in the 1890s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Starting in the first decade of the 20th century, friendlies were played between national teams of some European countries.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] While games like this did not take place in central and western Europe after the 1910s, the Nordic countries of Estonia, Finland, Norway, and Sweden continued, doing it more regularly during the 1920s and 1930s with annually or semi-annually recurring friendlies between some of them.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sweden tried to arrange for friendly games against the Soviet Union in the latter half of the 1940s, but it did not come to be until the mid-1950s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy was played as one of the sports at the Nordic Games, international winter sports events held during the first few decades of the 20th century.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Fédération internationale de hockey sur glace, or International Ice Hockey Federation as it is more well known as today, was founded in 1908 and was governing some bandy competitions in its early years, before only concentrating on ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Federation of International Bandy (FIB) was formed as *International Bandy Federation* in 1955 and has had 33 members at most, each representing a country where bandy is played.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Currently, there are 27 members of the federation.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The name of the federation was changed to the present one in 2001 after the International Olympic Committee approved it as a so-called "recognized sport".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The abbreviation "IBF" was at the time already used by another recognized sports federation, and IOC considers it important that the official abbreviations of sports federations are unique, so that the federations are not mistaken for one another.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] FIB is now a member of Association of IOC Recognised International Sports Federations.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Bandy World Championship for men is arranged by the FIB and was first held in 1957.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It was held every two years starting in 1961, and every year since 2003.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Currently, the record number of countries participating in the World Championships is twenty (2019).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Since the number of countries playing bandy is not large, every country which can set up a team is welcome to take part in the World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The quality of the teams varies; however, with only six nations, Sweden, the Soviet Union, Russia, Finland, Norway, and Kazakhstan, having won medals (allowing for the fact that Russia's team took over from the Soviet Union in 1993).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Finland won the 2004 world championship in Västerås, Sweden, while all other championships have been won by Sweden, the Soviet Union and Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Soviet Union won all championships until 1981, when Sweden managed to break the streak of eleven straight gold medals.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sweden won again in the next tournament in 1983, but Soviet again seized the victory in 1985.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Soviet Union also won at its last two appearances, and then Sweden won in 1993, 1995 and 1997.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Russia, having taken over after the Soviet Union, and Sweden have kept on winning all championships between them except for 2004, when Finland managed to claim the win.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In 2020, the B division of the World Championship was played, but the A division – which was to be played about a month later – was first postponed a couple of times due to the outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic and later moved to the next year as the pandemic did not end.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The championship tournament could however not be played in 2021 either.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The first World Championship for women took place in February 2004 in Lappeenranta, Finland.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Sweden won the championship without conceding a goal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In the 2014 women's World Championship Russia won for the first time, defeating Sweden, making it the first time Sweden did not win the world title.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The 2018 women's tournament was played in a country situated completely in Asia for the first time, when it was hosted in Chengde, China.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It was the same for the men's tournament that same year (the area north and west of the Ural River is located in Europe, thus Kazakhstan, which had hosted a world championship before, is a transcontinental country), when Harbin hosted the 2018 Division B tournament.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The 2020 championship saw China withdraw its participation due to the COVID-19 pandemic, but the tournament was held in Norway in February and the pandemic had not yet reached Europe.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In 2022 when the championship was played in Sweden, China did not yet return, while Russia and Ukraine both withdrew because of the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There are also Youth Bandy World Championships in different age groups for boys and young men and in one age group for girls.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The oldest group is the under 23 championship, Bandy World Championship Y-23.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] During most of the 20th century, a host nation for Olympic Games had the right to arrange demonstration games for almost any sport of its own choosing.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In 1952, the Winter Olympic Games were arranged in Oslo, Norway, and the Norwegians presented bandy as a demonstration sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The tournament of bandy at the 1952 Winter Olympics was played by three countries, Norway, Finland and Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This is the only time bandy has been played at Olympic Games.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy was officially recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) under the Association of IOC Recognised International Sports Federations (ARISF) in 2004, and was played as a demonstration sport at the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, it has yet to officially be played at the Olympics.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] According to the FIB, bandy is the world's second-most participated winter sport after ice hockey based on the number of participating athletes.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It is unclear how many of the players participate in the male category and how many in the female category.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The FIB has also recorded bandy (men's) as having ranked as the number two winter sport in terms of tickets sold per day of competitions at the sport's world championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, compared with the seven Winter Olympic sports, bandy's popularity among other winter sports across the globe is considered by the International Olympic Committee to have a, "gap between popularity and participation and global audiences", which is a roadblock to future Olympic inclusion.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In addition, the Olympic Charter requires a sport to be widely practiced by men in at least 75 countries and on four continents, and by women in no fewer than 40 countries and on three continents in order to be accepted.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] FIB president Boris Skrynnik lobbied for bandy to be included in the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi, given Russia's prominence in the sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Members of the Chinese Olympic Committee were present at the 2017 world championships to meet with Skrynnik about the possibility of considering the sport for the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, in 2018 it was announced no new sports would be added for 2022.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] At the 2011 Asian Winter Games, open to members of the Olympic Council of Asia, men's bandy was included for the first time.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Three teams contested the inaugural competition, and Kazakhstan won the gold medal.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The President of Kazakhstan, Nursultan Nazarbayev, attended the final.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There was no bandy competition at the next Games, the 2017 Asian Winter Games held in Japan.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Bandy made its debut at the Winter Universiade during the 2019 Games in Krasonyarsk, Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Originally a six-team tournament for men and a four-team tournament for women were planned to be held.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, later China withdrew from the men's tournament and was supposed to be replaced by Belarus.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Since that did not happen either, participating teams among women were Russia, Sweden, Norway and the United States, while among men Russia, Sweden, Norway, Finland and Kazakhstan.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The World Championships should not be confused with the annual Bandy World Cup competitions.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Bandy World Cup for men in Ljusdal, Sweden, has been played annually since the 1970s and is the biggest bandy tournament for elite-level club teams.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It is played indoors in Sandviken since 2009 because Ljusdal has no indoor arena.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It is expected to return to Ljusdal once an indoor arena has been built.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] World Cup matches are played day and night, and the tournament is played in four days in late October.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The teams participating are mostly, and some years exclusively, from Sweden and Russia, which has the two best leagues in the world.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic led to the Cup being cancelled in 2020 and 2021.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There is also a club competition for women's bandy teams called Bandy World Cup Women.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The European Cup was first played in 1974 and was a competition featuring the national men's champion team from any European country which had a national bandy championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This meant, at the time, that only four teams competed every year, which were the men's champions from Finland, Norway, the Soviet Union, and Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] After the Soviet Union had been dissolved in 1991, the Russian champions took part instead.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The cup is not formally defunct, but the last installment was played in 2009.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The Federation of International Bandy usually arranges a four nations tournament every year between national teams from Norway, Finland, Russia and Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The 2022 tournament was originally set for 21–23 January, but was cancelled after the Swedish Bandy Association announced they would not be hosting it for that season.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] During the period 1972–1990, the Rossiya Tournament was held semi-annually for national teams in the years when there was no world championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] This tournament was always played in the Soviet Union and arranged by the newspaper *Sovetskaya Rossiya*.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It was affectionately called "the small world championship".
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] From 1992 the tournament was renamed Russian Government Cup.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There has likely never been any European Championship played in bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Some sources describe a 1913 European Bandy Championships as having been held in February 1913, in Switzerland, at the same time as the bandy tournament at the 1913 Nordic Games.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] However, this European Championship tournament likely never happened, or is a conflation of titles, since no contemporary sources have been found.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There are several existing international bandy competitions with events varying based upon age, competitive level, and sex.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Varieties of bandy exist, utilising the same rules only with slight differences, like seven-a-side bandy with regulation sized goal cages but without corner strokes and often on a smaller sized rink.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Seven-a-side bandy was popular in central Europe and in England in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, while eleven-a-side bandy was preferred in the Nordic countries and in Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Seven-a-side bandy rules were applied at the Davos Cup in 2016.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Rink bandy is a bandy variant played on an ice hockey-size rink.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] It was originally conceived as a way of practicing bandy in the summertime, when there were no bandy sized indoor rinks but ice hockey rinks had started to be built indoors.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Rink bandy is played by basically the same rules as regular bandy but on a playing surface the size of an ice hockey rink with ice hockey goal cages and six players on each team (or five in the case of the USA Rink Bandy League).
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There have been international competitions for rink bandy played by the best bandy players in the 1980s and 1990s, both for club teams and for national teams, there were world championships in rink bandy in those days and the Hofors World Cup for clubs was played annually from 1984 to 1998.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] When more indoor bandy rinks have been built, rink bandy has more become a sport for lower league teams and recreational play.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Rink bandy was played in the 2012 European Company Sports Games program.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Czechia, the national federation has developed its own version of rink bandy with somewhat different rules, which is meant to help the players transition to playing on a full-sized bandy rink.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Read more in the section on Czechia below.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] Rink bandy has in turn led to the creation of the sport of rinkball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The sport of rinkball has at times been referred to as a variant of bandy, however it organized by the 1980s and has since become an established organized sport with its own governing body and differs considerably from both bandy and ice hockey, the sport's two major influences.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] In Sweden, informal games played like bandy but on ice-free ground (usually on gravel or asphalt concrete) are called *landbandy*.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] The term should not be confused with *landhockey*, the Swedish term for field hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There is no formal roller sport companion to bandy involving either inline skates or parallel wheel roller skates, even if rink hockey can be considered to have some similarities with bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p01] There is also no formally organized skateless ice variant of bandy, and bandy does not have any parasport variant.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy has been played in Canada since the 1980s, but is not nearly as popular as ice hockey in this country.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Friendlies are played against the United States.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Canadian bandy federation is called Canada Bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The China Bandy Federation was set up in 2014.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Since them, China has since participated in a number of world championship tournaments, with men's, women's and youth teams.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] China Bandy is mainly financed by private resources.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The development of the sport in China is supported by the Harbin Sport University.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A team from Prague in present-day Czechia became Austrian national bandy champions in 1911.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Czechia has been playing in the World Championship since 2016.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] As a way of preparing as well as possible for international matches, the Czechs have invented modified rules for games on ice hockey rinks, a variety called short bandy, which differs from rink bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Czech (former rink bandy) national league is now called *Liga českého národního bandy*.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was played in Estonia in the 1910s to 1930s and the country had a national championship for some years.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The national team played friendlies against Finland in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The sport was played sporadically during the Soviet occupation 1944–1991.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It has since then become more organized again, partly through exchange with Finnish clubs and enthusiasts.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] As of 2018, Estonia takes part in both the Bandy World Championship for men, and the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Finland from Russia in the 1890s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Finland has been playing bandy friendlies against Sweden and Estonia since its independence in 1917.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first men's Finnish national championships were held in 1908 and was the first national Finnish championship held in any team sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] National champions have been named every year except for three years in the first half of the 20th century when Finland was at war.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The top national league is called Bandyliiga and is semi-professional.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The best players turn fully professional by being recruited by clubs in Sweden or Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] As of the 2020–21 season, Bandyliiga consisted of the following teams: Akilles, Botnia-69, HIFK, JPS, Kampparit, Narukerä, OLS, Veiterä and WP 35.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Finland was an original member of the Federation of International Bandy and is the only country besides Russia/Soviet Union and Sweden to have won a Bandy World Championship, which it did in 2004.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Federation of International Bandy (FIB) is planning for a major premiere for indoor bandy in Finland in 2023 with the venue taking place at an indoor arena in Lappeenranta.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] When the arena is ready, an international inauguration is to take place with a 4-nation bandy tournament.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Participants will include teams from Russia, Sweden, Norway and Finland.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The tournament is scheduled for 20–22 January 2023.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy was played in Germany in the early 20th century, including by Crown Prince Wilhelm, but the interest died out in favour of ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Leipziger Sportclub, which arguably had the best team, was also the last club to give bandy up.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The sport was reintroduced to Germany in the 2010s, with the German Bandy Federation being founded in 2013.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Germany has been participating in the Bandy World Championship, a competition for male competitors, since 2014.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy is being played in northern parts of India close to the Himalayas, where there is usually cold weather and snow in the winter time.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A national championship is contested every year, but India has yet to send a national team to the World Championships or any other international competition.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy has a long history in many parts of Kazakhstan and it used to be one of the most popular sports in Soviet times.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, after independence it suffered a rapid decline in popularity and only remained in Oral (often called by the Russian name, "Uralsk"), where the country's only professional club Akzhaiyk is located.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] They presently compete in the Russian second tier division, the Russian Bandy Supreme League.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Recently bandy has started to gain popularity again outside of Oral, most notably in Petropavl and Khromtau.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Those were for example the three Kazakh cities which had players in the team at the Youth-17, Youth Bandy World Championship for boys in 2016.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The capital Astana has hosted national youth championships in rink bandy as well as championships in traditional eleven-a-side bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In recent years the former capital Almaty has hosted both the Asian Winter Games (with bandy on the program) as well as the Bandy World Championship for men in which Kazakhstan finished 3rd.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Plans are being made to reinvigorate the bandy section of the club Dynamo Almaty, who won the Soviet Championships in 1977 and 1990 as well as the European Cup in 1978.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Almaty is also the home of the headquarters of the Asian Bandy Federation.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Since bandy began regaining popularity and acceptance, the state has begun supporting bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Medeu in Almaty is the only arena with artificial ice.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A second arena in Almaty was built for the World Championship 2012, but it was taken down afterwards.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Stadion Yunost in Oral was supposed to get artificial ice for the 2017–18 season.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It got delayed but in 2018 it was officially ready for use.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The national team took a silver medal at the 2011 Asian Winter Games, which led to being chosen as the best Mongolian sport team of 2011.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Mongolia was proud to win the bronze medal of the B division at the 2017 Bandy World Championship after which the President of Mongolia, Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj, held a reception for the team.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to the Netherlands in the 1890s by Pim Mulier and the sport became popular.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, in the 1920s, the interest turned to ice hockey, but in contrast to other countries in central and western Europe, the sport has been continuously played in the Netherlands and since the 1970s, the country has become a member of FIB and games have been more formalised again.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The national team started to compete at the WCS in 1991.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, without a proper venue, only rink bandy is played within the country.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The national governing body is the Bandy Bond Nederland.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Norway in the 1910s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Swedes contributed largely and clubs sprang up around the capital of Kristiania (present day Oslo).
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Oslo, including neighbouring towns, is in the twenty-first century still the region where bandy enjoys most popularity in Norway.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 1912 the Norwegians played their first National Championship, which was played annually up to 1940.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] During World War II, when Norway was occupied by Germany, illegal bandy was played in hidden places in forests, on ponds and lakes.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 1943, 1944 and 1945, illegal championships were held.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 1946 legal play resumed and still goes on in form of the Norwegian Bandy Premier League (*Eliteserien*).
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] After World War II the number of teams rose, as well as attendance which regularly were in the thousands, but mild winters in the 1970s and 1980s shrunk the league, and in 2003 only five clubs (teams) fought out the 1st division with low attendance numbers and little media coverage.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] As of 2021 there are 10 teams in the Norwegian Bandy Premier League.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Norway's best result in the World Championship is a second place in 1965.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Norwegian bandy champion is decided each year by a play-off among the best teams in the Norwegian Bandy Premier League.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first Norwegian bandy champions was decided in 1912 and the championship has been held almost every year since.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Until 1928, the championship was played as 7-a-side bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In Russia bandy is known as hockey with a ball or simply Russian hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A similar game became popular among the Russian nobility in the early 1700s, with the imperial court of Peter the Great playing a predecessor of modern bandy on Saint Petersburg's frozen Neva river.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Russians initially played this game using ordinary footwear with sticks made out of juniper wood, but it wasn't until later that ice skates were introduced.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy did not become popular among the masses throughout the Russian Empire until the second half of the 19th century.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The predecessor of the current Russian Bandy Federation was founded in 1898.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy is considered a national sport in Russia and is the only discipline to have official support of the Russian Orthodox Church.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Traditionally the Russians used a longer skate blade than other nations, giving them the advantage of skating faster.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, they would find it more difficult to turn quickly.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A bandy skate has a longer blade than an ice hockey skate, and the "Russian skate" is even longer.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Though bandy was still played in the Soviet Union after the Russian Revolution, they did not partake in any international games for many decades.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While agreements had previously been made to play friendlies against Sweden in the late 1940s, these plans had not come to fruition.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The bandy event at the 1952 Winter Olympics in Oslo, Norway, where men's bandy featured as a demonstration sport, was played without any Soviet team.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, the Soviets reconsidered their position following this competition.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] When the Federation of International Bandy was formed in 1955, with the Soviet Union as one of its founding members, the Russians largely adopted the international rules of the game developed in England in the 19th century, with one notable exception.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The other countries adopted the border which until then had only been used in Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The men's Russian professional bandy league is called the Russian Bandy Super League.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Russian Bandy Supreme League is the second tier of men's Russian bandy, below the Russian Bandy Super League.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In Sweden, the Elitserien (literally, the "Elite League") is the highest bandy league in the country for men, while Bandyallsvenskan is the second division.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In Finland, the highest bandy league for men is the Bandyliiga.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In a similar fashion, Russia, along with Sweden, has emerged as one of the two dominant women's bandy nations internationally, regularly placing first or second at the premier international bandy competition for women, the Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] He talked, among other things, about the need to give more support to Russian bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It was the first time a head of state had accepted a meeting to talk about Russian bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Attending the meeting were also Minister of Sport, Tourism and Youth policy Vitaly Mutko and presidential adviser Igor Levitin.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The month after, Igor Levitin held a follow-up meeting.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Russian Bandy Super League is the top tier of the Russian bandy league system.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It is professional and played every year.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The winner in the final becomes Russian champion.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It is considered a continuation of the Soviet Union championship, which was played annually until the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Russian Cup has been played annually most years since 1937, originally called the Soviet Cup.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy as an organized sport was introduced to Sweden in 1895.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Swedish royal family, noblemen and diplomats were among the first players.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While the original inspiration mainly came from England, there also were early exchanges with Germany and Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy was taken up as one of the sports at the international Nordic Games held in Sweden semi-annually from 1901.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Swedish championships for men have been played annually since 1907 and Sweden was the first country to have an annual bandy league.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In the 1920s students played the game, then it spread across the country and became a largely middle-class sport.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The games could attract huge crowds of spectators in those days.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] After Slottsbrons IF won the Swedish championship in 1934 it became popular amongst workers in many smaller industrial towns and villages.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Where there was a bandy club the local factory corporation also usually sponsored the club to mutual benefit as a successful team led to good PR for the company.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy remains the main sport in many of these places.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In the mid-20th Century, bandy was the most popular spectator sport in Sweden, drawing huge crowds for most events and having bigger audiences than football or ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While not having the same numbers now, bandy is increasing the number of spectators in the 2020s, in contrast to many other sports.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy in Sweden is famous for its "culture" where both playing bandy and being a spectator requires great fortitude and dedication.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A bandyportföljen is the classic accessory for spectating and is typically made of brown leather, well worn, and contains a warm drink in a thermos and/or a bottle of liquor.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy is most often played at outdoor arenas during winter time, so the need for spectators to carry flasks or thermoses of 'warming' liquid like glögg is a natural effect.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] With the sport moving indoors in recent decades and the arenas urging for non-alcoholic policies for the audiences, this tradition has partly changed, though not without opposition.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A notable tradition is "annandagsbandy", bandy games played on Saint Stephen's Day (*annandagen* = ’the second day [of Christmas]’), which for many Swedes is an important Christmas season tradition and always draws bigger crowds than usual.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Elite League is the top tier of Swedish bandy and is fully professional.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] At the end of the season, a play-off is made to make out the two teams playing the final match for the Swedish Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Final is played every year on the third Saturday of March.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] From 1991 to 2012, it was played at Studenternas Idrottsplats in Uppsala, often drawing crowds in excess of 20,000.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] One reason the play-off match was set in Uppsala is because of IFK Uppsala's success at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] IFK Uppsala won 11 titles in the Swedish Championships between 1907 and 1920, which made them the most successful bandy club in the entire country (now, however, the record is held by Västerås SK).
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A contributing factor was also the poor quality of the ice at Söderstadion, where the finals were held from 1967 to 1989.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 2013 and 2014 the final was played indoors in Friends Arena, the national stadium for football in Solna, Stockholm, with a retractable roof and a capacity of 50,000.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first final at Friends Arena in 2013 drew a record crowd of 38,474 when Hammarby IF Bandy, after ending up in second place in six finals during the 2000s, won their second title.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Due to declining attendance from 2015 through 2017 Tele2 Arena in southern Stockholm was chosen as a new venue.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, the new indoor venue failed to attract much more than half of the total capacity.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In May 2017 it was announced that the finals will again be held at Studenternas IP in Uppsala from 2018 through at least 2021.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The *Svenska Cupen* (English: The Swedish Cup), *Svenska Cupen i bandy*, takes place exclusively in Sweden.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It is a single-elimination tournament competition in Swedish bandy and the second-most prominent bandy competition which is open only to domestic Swedish teams, after the national championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first women's competition was played in 2019.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In the late nineteenth and early 20th century, Switzerland had become a popular place for winter vacations and people went there from all over Europe.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Winter sports like skiing, sledding and bandy was played in Geneva and other towns.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Students from Oxford and Cambridge went to Switzerland to play each other – the predecessor of the recurring Ice Hockey Varsity Match was a bandy match played in St.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] This popularity for Swiss venues of winter sport may have been a reason, the European Championship was held there in 1913.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy has mainly been played as a recreational sport in Switzerland in the 2000s and 2010s.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A Swiss men's national team was finally started up in 2017 and a Swiss women's national team made its international début in the 2018 Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy was played in Ukraine when it was part of the Soviet Union.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] After independence in 1991, it took some years before organized bandy formed again, but Ukrainian champions have been named annually since 2012.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first recorded games of what may be considered bandy on ice took place in The Fens during the great frost of 1813–1814, although it is probable that the game had already been played there in the previous century.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bury Fen Bandy Club from Bluntisham-cum-Earith, near St Ives, was the most successful team, said to have remained unbeaten for a hundred years until the winter of 1890–1891.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Charles Goodman Tebbutt of the Bury Fen Bandy Club was responsible for the first published rules of bandy in 1882, and also for introducing the game into the Netherlands and Sweden, as well as elsewhere in England where it became popular with cricket, rowing, and hockey clubs.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Tebbutt's homemade bandy stick can be seen in the Norris Museum in St Ives.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first Ice Hockey Varsity Matches between Oxford University and Cambridge University were played to bandy rules, even if it was called hockey on the ice at the time.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It is sometimes claimed that a national team for England won the European Bandy Championships in 1913, but that tournament likely never took place.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While bandy is often thought to have been a popular sport in England in the decades around 1900, few records seem to have been kept.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A statue of a bandy player, designed by Peter Baker, was erected at the village pond of Earith to commemorate the 200th anniversary of the first documented game in 2013.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In March 2004, Norwegian ex-player Edgar Malman invited two big clubs to play a rink bandy exhibition game in Streatham, London.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Russian Champions and World Cup Winner Vodnik met Swedish Champions Edsbyns IF in a match that ended 10–10.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 2010 England became a Federation of International Bandy member.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The national federation is based in Cambridgeshire, the historical heartland.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The England Bandy Federation, was set up on 2 January 2017 at a meeting held in the historic old skaters public house, the Lamb and Flag in Welney in Norfolk, England, replacing the Bandy Federation of England which had been founded in 2010 but had had dwindling activity.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In September 2017, the federation decided to widen its territory to all of the United Kingdom and changed its name to Great Britain Bandy Association.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Great Britain entered a national team in the 2019 World Championships Group B in January and undefeated up to the final, won the silver medal in their final match against Estonia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] They were set to return to the 2020 World Championships, but were refused visas to Russia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] However, the comeback will come in 2025.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] In 2022, Great Britain premiered its national women's bandy team at the 2022 Women's Bandy World Championship.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy in its original, informal manner disappeared from the North American continent entirely once it and elements from the early game had become absorbed into a new sport of ice hockey.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While ice hockey was growing and organizing in the United States, bandy was doing the same, but only in Europe and Scandinavia.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It would not arrive in its organized format in the United States until the 1970s, almost a century after its initial development.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Bandy has been played in the United States since around the 1970s, after its promotion by Russians, Swedes and Finns in an exchange with softball, a sport which was promoted by Americans during the same time in the Soviet Union, Sweden and Finland.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] A key-person in the establishment of the sport in America was Bob Kojetin of Minnesota Softball.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The sport is centered in Minnesota, with very few teams based elsewhere.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The United States national bandy team has participated in the Bandy World Championships since 1985 and is also regularly playing friendly matches against Canada.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The leading organization for bandy in the US is USA Bandy.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The US has a men's national bandy team and a women's national bandy team.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The first bandy game in the US was played in December 1979 at the Lewis Park Bandy Rink in Edina, Minnesota.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] It was a friendly game between the Swedish junior national team and Swedish club team Brobergs IF.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] United States bandy championships have been played annually since the early 1980s, but the sport is not widely covered by American sports media.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The championship trophy is called the Gunnar Cup, named after Gunnar Fast, a Swedish army captain who helped introduce bandy to the United States around 1980.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] While North American ice hockey rinks can be used for playing the bandy variant of rink bandy, places where the traditional game of bandy can be played require a larger sized playing surface, a bandy field, and are almost non-existent in North America.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] Minnesota is home to the only regulation sized bandy "rink" in North America, the Guidant John Rose Minnesota Oval, commonly referred to as, "The Oval", and is also the largest outdoor refrigerated skating rink in North America.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The rink is 10,219 square meters with more than 800 tons of refrigeration and 135 km of pipes underneath the ice.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The ice can be maintained in temperatures up to +10 degrees Celsius.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Oval can hold up to 300 spectators and has hosted World Cup Speedskating, the 2016 Women's Bandy World Championship, and Aggressive Skating/Biking competitions.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The Oval is used mostly for inline hockey during the summer.
[src:bandy/bandy-p02] The following associations are the governing bodies for bandy in different countries and are member organizations of the Federation of International Bandy.
